## Summary

Implements agent-scoped Policy overlays under `scopes.agents.<scopeName>` for the policy sections whose evidence is already attributable to runtime agent ids: `tools` and `agents.workspace`.

Each named scope lists the runtime agent ids it applies to with `agentIds`. The scope name is descriptive only; matching uses normalized OpenClaw agent ids, not display names. Multiple scope blocks may target the same agent when they govern different fields, but the same effective agent cannot receive the same scoped policy field from more than one scope block.

The overlay model is additive: top-level `tools.*` and `agents.workspace` claims still run, while scoped `tools` and `agents.workspace` blocks can add stricter claims and emit their own findings against the same observed config. Unsupported scoped sections and unsupported scoped `tools` keys are rejected rather than silently ignored.

`tools.alsoAllow.expected` is supported as an exact-list conformance claim. It reports missing expected additive grants and unexpected extra additive grants, including the empty-list case where policy expects no `alsoAllow` entries.

Example:

```jsonc
{
  "tools": {
    "exec": { "allowHosts": ["gateway", "sandbox"] },
    "alsoAllow": { "expected": [] }
  },
  "agents": {
    "workspace": { "allowedAccess": ["none", "ro"] }
  },
  "scopes": {
    "agents": {
      "production-workspace": {
        "agentIds": ["sebastian-prod", "buddy"],
        "agents": {
          "workspace": { "allowedAccess": ["none", "ro"] }
        }
      },
      "sebby-node-tools": {
        "agentIds": ["sebastian-prod"],
        "tools": {
          "exec": { "allowHosts": ["node"] },
          "alsoAllow": { "expected": ["lobster"] }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

In this example, `sebastian-prod` receives both the shared `production-workspace` claim and the narrower `sebby-node-tools` claim, while `buddy` only receives the shared workspace claim. That demonstrates overlapping scopes without duplicating the same effective policy field for the same agent.

## Verification

- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check --threads=1 docs/cli/policy.md docs/plugins/reference/policy.md docs/plan/policy-agent-scoped-overlays.md extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.ts extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.test.ts`
- `pnpm exec oxlint extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.ts extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.test.ts`
- `pnpm docs:check-mdx docs/cli/policy.md docs/plugins/reference/policy.md docs/plan/policy-agent-scoped-overlays.md`
- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/policy/src/doctor/register.test.ts -- --runInBand --reporter=dot`

## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: Policy conformance can now express stricter workspace and tool posture claims for named policy scopes that target explicit runtime agent ids without weakening deployment-wide policy claims.
Real environment tested: WSL checkout at `/root/src/openclaw-policy-agent-scoped-design` on Ubuntu-24.04.
Exact steps or command run after this patch: Ran MDX validation, Markdown formatting, focused lint, and focused Policy plugin doctor tests against the pushed commit.
Evidence after fix: Policy shape validation accepts `scopes.agents.<scopeName>.agentIds`, `scopes.agents.<scopeName>.tools`, and `scopes.agents.<scopeName>.agents.workspace`; missing/empty/duplicate normalized `agentIds` are rejected; overlapping scope blocks are accepted for different fields and rejected for duplicate effective fields on the same normalized agent; scoped findings match normalized runtime agent ids.
Observed result after fix: 163 focused Vitest tests pass; docs checks, formatting checks, and focused lint pass.
What was not tested: Full repository test suite; this change is scoped to Policy plugin conformance and policy docs.

